snippet.textDisplay: I love this movie and I loved hearing your thoughts on it! Buuuuuut... saying the movie didn't come down too hard on one side or the other in the "immigration subplot" is disingenuous: Marta is good in many ways because she is an immigrant, because she's lived through hardships with her mother and sister and because she's worked hard to get where she is! The Thrombeys are almost all asshats because they are rich, which is Harlan's whole point: he handed them everything they could ever want in life on a silver platter and that made them self-absorbed, bigoted, lazy and greedy. You have a tendency of trying to come across as centrist in a lot of these videos, and on this platform of all platforms I get it, but it's okay to acknowledge the themes and messages of a story in more detail, especially when they're all but spelled out for you lmao. Keep up the good work, I'm definitely gonna keep on watching <3

snippet.textDisplay: A lot of people write off the immigration subplot as "just another way RUIN Johnson is pandering to liberal Hollywood" but if you're paying attention it's way deeper and smarter than that. Like you pointed out, what sets Marta apart from the Thrombeys is that she's a genuinely good person, completely divorced from any political ideology, whereas every member of the family clearly feels superior, and uses their political beliefs to justify it. But when push comes to shove, and the Thrombeys feel threatened they all backslide into taking a decidedly anti-immigration stance to get their money back, revealing that they're not good people, regardless of how they think their politics defines them. Of course this is also layered in with moments like none of the Thrombeys knowing where Marta is from, or by treating her like the maid, but I think it was smart to have it laid out plainly, and let members of the audience sympathize with various members of the family depending on their personal beliefs, and have the rug ripped out from under them when the whole family turns on Marta. Anyways, this script is brilliant, and I hope people were able to set aside their personal biases towards Rian Johnson and just enjoy the movie on its own terms.

snippet.textDisplay:
While I still don't want Rian Johnson near Star Wars ever again (my opinion, to each their own), this was honestly such a good movie. I loved seeing it unfold and getting to watch Martha be proven to be the good character I knew she was from the beginning. I never had a doubt that she was innocent, because that's just who she is. Honestly, I guessed right from the beginning that Chris Evans was the killer because despite other huge names on the film like Jamie Lee Curtis, Chris was the one to get the most screentime. He just came off of Avengers, he was gonna get the biggest part he could, which was the villain only second to Martha and Daniel Craig's detective. I also called the fake knife bit way early. My family was so shocked but I was laughing as soon as he lunged at her. My only complaint about this movie is that I was left wondering about Meg by the end. I felt totally unsure about whether or not she cared for Martha. To me, it seemed like she genuinely liked Martha and was coerced into getting the money back by her family, but the ending made it seem like she was also meant to be as cruel as her family members so I'm not sure what to believe.
All in all though, props the the cast and Rian Johnson. You did good man, and I look forward to seeing more films like this one.



Just not in Star Wars.
